      {
         "text": "<p><img id=\"imgHn0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHn0', '0%')\" src=\"images/eLife/elife-09560-fig1-v1.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 3</b>: The figure includes approximately all the material incorporated into this diagnosis, including the holotype specimen, paratypes, and referred material. These comprise 737 partial or complete anatomical elements, many of which consist of several reassembled specimens. Specimens not identified to the element level, such as non-diagnostic long bones or cranial fragments, and a subset of fragile specimens are not shown here. The arrangement of the ‘skeleton’ in the center of the photo is a composite of elements representing multiple individuals. This view is in perspective; the table on which the bones are arranged is 120 cm wide for scale reference. © Lee Roger Berger research team (<htcite0>). Shared under <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike</a> license.</p>",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "a32b3d0b-9a93-421d-b313-7c455b356531",
               "text": "Berger, L. R. et al.",
               "page": "pp. 4",
               "date_time": {
