      {
         "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: How so?</b><br /><br />Imagine a place where it is impossible to prove that any of your ancestors ever lived—whether a recent or distant ancestor, over thousands of years.<br /><br />Do you believe you have any right to that land?<br /><br />What if someone who had also never been there wrote on a piece of paper that the place belongs to them? Would you feel comfortable going there and taking possession?<br /><br />If you arrived and found people living there for thousands of years, what would you do?</div></div></center></p>",
         "source": null,
         "date_time": null,
         "isTable": false,
         "imgdesc": "",
         "format": "html",
         "PostMention": ""
      },
      {
         "text": "The drafting of the Treaty of Tordesillas became problematic for the peoples who would be colonized—but not only for them. By imposing limits on the “division of the world” between just two kingdoms, the French king Francis I questioned it ironically, based on the worldview of the time: “The sun shines for me as for others. I would like to see the clause in Adam’s will that excludes me from the division of the world” (<htcite0>).\n\nTo conclude this introduction, it is important to note that the “division of the world” by Europeans did not imply immediate submission or acceptance by other peoples. In this text, we will explore the Mutapa State, which resisted colonialism until the 19th century, according to the Gregorian calendar (<htcite1>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "bbe95945-abbb-4247-b1eb-5353831fc1ba",
               "text": "Hervé Théry",
               "page": "",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "2019",
                  "month": "",
                  "day": ""
               }
            },
